{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20141112145629|633530411","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Pete_Gallego","to":"Pete Gallego"}],"pages":{"15908202":{"pageid":15908202,"ns":0,"title":"Pete Gallego","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2014-11-19T22:29:12Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{Infobox Officeholder \n| name         = Pete P. Gallego\n| image        = Pete Gallego official portrait.jpg\n|office        = Member of the [[U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from Texas's [[Texas's 23rd congressional district|23rd]] district\n|term_start    = January 3, 2013\n|term_end      = <!--January 3, 2015-->\n|preceded      = [[Quico Canseco]]\n|succeeded =  [[Will Hurd]] <small>(elect)</small>\n| state_house2 = Texas\n| state2       = Texas\n| district2    = 74th\n| term_start2  = 1991\n| term_end2    = 2013\n| preceded2    =\n| succeeded2   =\n| party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1961|12|02}}\n| birth_place  = [[Alpine, Texas]]\n| death_date   =\n| death_place  =\n| residence    = [[Alpine, Texas]]\n| spouse       = Maria Elena Ramon\n| profession   = [[Attorney at law (United States)|Attorney]]\n| religion     = [[Roman Catholic]]\n| website      = [http://gallego.house.gov/ Representative Pete Gallego]\n|}}\n\n'''Pete P. Gallego''' (born December 2, 1961) is an [[United States|American]] politician who has been the [[U.S. House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for [[Texas's 23rd congressional district]] since 2013. Gallego, a member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], previously served as a member of the [[Texas House of Representatives]] from the 74th district beginning in 1991.\n\nGallego defeated freshman incumbent [[Quico Canseco]] of [[San Antonio, Texas|San Antonio]] for [[Texas's 23rd congressional district]] seat in the November 6, 2012, [[general election]]. Canseco conceded the race on November 9.<ref>{{cite news|last=Martin|first=Gary|title=Canseco concedes to Gallego in District 23|url=http://www.mysanantonio.com/news/local_news/article/Canseco-concedes-to-Gallego-in-District-23-4023778.php|accessdate=22 May 2014|newspaper=San Antonio Express-News|date=11-9-2012}}</ref> Gallego ran for re-election in 2014, in what the ''[[Texas Tribune]]'' called the \"only obviously competitive November congressional race\" in Texas.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ramsey|first=Ross|title=Analysis: Down the Ballot, Few Races in November|url=http://www.texastribune.org/2014/04/30/analysis-down-ballot-few-races-november/|accessdate=22 May 2014|newspaper=Texas Tribune|date=2014-04-30}}</ref>  He was defeated by Republican [[Will Hurd]] on November 4, 2014.\n\n==Early career==\nAfter graduating law school, Gallego became an assistant in the Attorney General\u2019s office, before returning to his hometown of Alpine to become a prosecutor. He is also an attorney at the law firm Brown McCarroll LLP, with an office in Austin.<ref name=journal/><ref name=nationaljournal>{{cite news|last1=McClane|first1=Brianna|title=Texas, 23rd House District|url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/congress/texas-23rd-house-district-20121101|accessdate=19 August 2014|publisher=National Journal|date=11-1-2012}}</ref>\n\n==State legislature==\nElected to the Texas House from District 74 in 1990, Gallego was the first [[Hispanic]] to represent this vast border district. In 1991, he became the first freshman member and the first ethnic minority member ever elected as chair of the House Democratic Caucus, a post he held until January 2001.<ref name=journal>{{cite web|title=Pete Gallego (D)|url=http://projects.wsj.com/campaign2012/candidates/view/pete-gallego--TX-H|work=Election 2012|publisher=Wall Street Journal}}</ref>\n\nIn the Texas House, Gallego served on the board of directors of the [[National Association of Latino Elected Officials]] (NALEO), and four terms as Chairman of the [[Mexican American Legislative Caucus]] (MALC), a caucus of Texas representatives who are of Mexican-American descent or who serve a significant Mexican-American constituency. In 2008, [[Trey Martinez Fischer]] replaced Gallego as Chairman of MALC.<ref name=journal/><ref>{{cite news|last=Glazer|first=Matt|title=Mexican American Legislative Caucus (MALC) Elects New Leadership|url=http://www.burntorangereport.com/diary/7597/|accessdate=22 May 2014|newspaper=Burnt Orange Report|date=12-9-2008}}</ref>\n\nGallego's state legislative career included chairmanships of the General Investigating Committee and several select and subcommittees.{{cn|date=September 2014}} He has also served as a member of the Committees on Appropriations, Calendars, Criminal Jurisprudence, Higher Education, and Elections.{{cn|date=September 2014}}\n\nIn 2008, Gallego narrowly missed being elected [[Speaker of the Texas House of Representatives|Speaker of the Texas House]].<ref name=announce>Marty Schladen. [http://www.elpasotimes.com/news/ci_24352017/veteran-moderate-wants-help-fix-congress US Rep. Pete Gallego wants to help fix Congress]. ''El Paso Times'', 10/21/2013.</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n;2012\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Texas, 2012#District 23}}\nGallego announced his candidacy for the 23rd district in September 2011.<ref name=announce>Perry, Mike. [http://alpinedailyplanet.typepad.com/alpine-daily-planet/2011/09/gallego-makes-it-official-hes-running-for-us-congress.html Gallego makes it official: He's running for U.S. Congress]. ''Alpine Daily Planet'', 2011-09-01.</ref> His state house district was virtually coextensive with the central portion of the congressional district.\n\nHe finished second in the Democratic primary, behind former congressman [[Ciro Rodriguez]], who had received [[Bill Clinton]]\u2019s endorsement. He then defeated Rodriguez in the July 31 runoff election by a margin of 55-45 percent.<ref>[http://elections.sos.state.tx.us/elchist.exe 2012 Democratic Party Primary Runoff 7/31/2012]</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Martin|first1=Gary|title=Gallego beats Rodriguez to challenge Canseco in the fall|url=http://www.mysanantonio.com/news/local_news/article/Gallego-beats-Rodriguez-to-challenge-Canseco-in-3752147.php|accessdate=19 August 2014|publisher=MySanAntonio|date=8-1-2012}}</ref> During the course of his campaign, Gallego overhauled his campaign staff four times.<ref name=campaign>{{cite news|last=Martin|first=Gary|title=Pete Gallego overhauls congressional campaign a fourth time|url=http://blog.mysanantonio.com/texas-on-the-potomac/2012/08/pete-gallego-overhauls-congressional-campaign-a-fourth-time/|accessdate=22 May 2014|newspaper=San Antonio Express-News|date=2012-08-16}}</ref>\n\nIn the general election, Gallego defeated Canseco with 50 percent of the vote to Canseco's 46 percent, a margin of 9,200 votes.  While Gallego lost in [[Bexar County]], home to more than half the district's population, he dominated his former state house district. The campaign between Gallego and Canseco was contentious, with Gallego alleging that Canseco was a \"right-wing extremist,\" and Canseco calling Gallego a \"radical environmentalist.\"<ref name=campaign/><ref>{{cite news|last=Martin|first=Gary|title=Gallego starts swinging at Canseco in 23rd congressional race|url=http://www.mysanantonio.com/news/local_news/article/Gallego-starts-swinging-at-Canseco-in-23rd-3755212.php|accessdate=22 May 2014|newspaper=San Antonio News-Express|date=8-1-2012}}</ref>\n\nGallego was supported by the [[Blue Dog Coalition]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Trujillo|first=Mario|title=Blue Dog Democrats fight for relevance|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/house/269155-blue-dogs-fight-for-relevance-as-minority-group-in-minority-party-|accessdate=22 May 2014|newspaper=The Hill|date=2012-11-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Beard|first1=Sterling|title=Rep. Gallego enjoys rare status as a new Texas Democrat in the House  |url=http://thehill.com/capital-living/new-member-of-the-week/295179-rep-gallego-enjoys-rare-status-as-a-new-texas-democrat-in-the-house|accessdate=19 August 2014|publisher=The Hill|date=2013-04-22}}</ref>\n\n;2014\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Texas, 2014#District 23}}\nGallego is running for re-election in 2014. Facing no opposition from his own party, he won the Democratic primary on March 4, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pete P. Gallego's Political Summary|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/5505/pete-gallego#.U35D9C8wlUE|publisher=Project Vote Smart|accessdate=22 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Grissom|first1=Brandi|title=Liveblog: 2014 Primary Election|url=http://www.texastribune.org/2014/03/04/liveblog-primary-election-2014/|accessdate=19 August 2014|publisher=Texas Tribune|date=3-4-2014}}</ref> He faces Republican [[Will Hurd]], an [[African American]], in the general election.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Delreal|first1=Jose|title=Will Hurd wins TX-23 rematch against Francisco \"Quico\" Canseco|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2014/05/will-hurd-texas-francisco-quico-canseco-107142.html|accessdate=19 August 2014|publisher=Politico|date=2014-05-27}}</ref> Gallego is a member of the [[Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee|Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee's]] Frontline Program. The program is designed to help protect vulnerable Democratic incumbents.  He still lost his bid for re-election to Republican Will Hurd by less than 2,500 votes.  <ref>{{cite news|last=Isenstadt|first=Alex|title=Democrats launching plan for 2014 at-risk members|url=http://www.politico.com//story/2013/03/democrats-launching-plan-for-2014-at-risk-members-88402.html|accessdate=22 May 2014|newspaper=Politico|date=3-4-2013}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Agriculture|Committee on Agriculture]]'''\n**[[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on General Farm Commodities and Risk Management|Subcommittee on General Farm Commodities and Risk Management]]\n**[[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on Livestock, Rural Development, and Credit|Subcommittee on Livestock, Rural Development, and Credit]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Armed Services|Committee on Armed Services]]'''\n**[[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Tactical Air and Land Forces|Subcommittee on Tactical Air and Land Forces]]\n**[[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Readiness|Subcommittee on Readiness]]\n\n==Political positions==\n\n===Healthcare===\nGallego opposes repeal of the [[Affordable Care Act]] and voted against repeal in May 2013.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0o7Iytm1hRI | title=TribLive: Gallego on Obamacare, Iran and Taxes | publisher=YouTube | accessdate=2013-11-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2013/roll154.xml | title=Final Vote Results for Roll Call 154 | publisher=House.gov | accessdate=2013-11-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Garcia|first1=Gilbert|title=Gallego's no-win situation on health care law|url=http://www.expressnews.com/news/news_columnists/gilbert_garcia/article/Gallego-s-no-win-situation-on-health-care-law-4936931.php|accessdate=19 August 2014|publisher=San Antonio Express-News|date=2013-10-29}}</ref> Gallego's support for the Affordable Care Act has been attacked in advertisements by the Libre Initiative, a conservative Hispanic outreach group.<ref>{{cite news|last=Schladen|first=Marty|title=Libre Initiative targets Obama's Affordable Care Act|url=http://www.elpasotimes.com/news/ci_25096319/el-paso-times|accessdate=22 May 2014|newspaper=El Paso Times|date=2014-02-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Pabst|first=Georgia|title=Libre Initiative reaches out to Hispanics with free-enterprise message|url=http://www.jsonline.com/news/milwaukee/libre-initiative-reaches-out-to-hispanics-with-free-enterprise-message-b99210747z1-246796021.html|accessdate=22 May 2014|newspaper=Milwaukee Journal Sentinel|date=2014-02-23}}</ref>\n\nGallego opposes a Medicare voucher system<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hennessy-Fiske|first1=Molly|title=Texas congressional candidates debate -- in Spanish|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2012/sep/26/nation/la-na-nn-texas-debate-spanish-20120926|accessdate=19 August 2014|publisher=Los Angeles Times|date=2012-09-26}}</ref> and says that he supports Medicaid expansion and prescription drug negotiations.<ref>{{cite web|title=Issues: Medicare|url=http://petegallego.com/issues/medicare|work=Campaign Website|publisher=Pete Gallego|accessdate=22 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n===LGBT issues===\nGallego opposes gay marriage, stating, \u201cI have never been in favor of gay marriage and I am not in favor of gay marriage.\" Gallego supports civil unions for same-sex couples.<ref name=nationaljournal/><ref name=\"mailer\"/>\n\n===Abortion===\nGallego supported an abortion law allowing minors to get an abortion with parental consent. Under the legislation a minor would have been able to bypass the requirement for parental consent by petitioning a judge.<ref name=nationaljournal/><ref name=\"mailer\">{{cite news|last=Root|first=Jay|title=Gallego: Jesus Would Not Like Political Mailer|url=http://www.texastribune.org/2012/10/16/gallego-jesus-would-not-political-mailer/|accessdate=22 May 2014|newspaper=Texas Tribune|date=2012-10-16}}</ref>\n\n===Immigration===\nGallego has said that border security and immigration reform are two separate issues. He advocates improved \u201cworker accountability programs, using border security as an economic tool and aiding the current 11 million undocumented individuals in a path to citizenship\u201d, writing with several others in an opinion piece in the ''El Paso Times'' that, \"We can no longer delay immigration reform. The time to move forward is now.\" Gallego has said \"Most people don\u2019t really care where the idea comes from. They want action, they want something to happen, and they\u2019re tired of the prolonged conversation.\" Gallego has expressed support for President Obama's immigration policies. He supports the [[DREAM Act]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Sullivan|first=Alison|title=Pete Gallego: People want action on immigration reform, not prolonged debate|url=http://blog.chron.com/txpotomac/2013/02/pete-gallego-people-want-action-on-immigration-reform-not-prolonged-debate/#9023101=0|accessdate=22 May 2014|newspaper=Houston Chronicle|date=2013-2-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Borunda|first=Daniel|title=State of the Union: Beto O'Rourke, Pete Gallego cheer immigration reform push|url=http://www.elpasotimes.com/ci_22578887/orourke-gallego-cheer-immigration-reform-push|accessdate=22 May 2014|newspaper=El Paso Times|date=2-12-2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Gallego invited Speaker of the House John Boehner to the Southern Border to view the humanitarian crisis and discuss the matter with local border patrol agents and community members.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Dumain|first1=Emma|title=Freshman Democrat Invites Speaker to Southwest Border|url=http://blogs.rollcall.com/218/freshman-democrat-invites-house-speaker-to-southwest-border/?dcz=|website=www.rollcall.com|publisher=Roll Call|accessdate=7 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Energy===\nGallego has been supported by the [[Sierra Club]] and the [[League of Conservation Voters]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Colman|first=Zack|title=Green groups tout election results as victory for clean energy|url=http://thehill.com/policy/energy-environment/266537-green-groups-best-fossil-fuel-industry-in-down-ballot-races|accessdate=22 May 2014|newspaper=The Hill|date=11-7-2012}}</ref> According to ''Texas Climate News'', Gallego's 2012 congressional victory \"earned the celebratory attention of climate-action advocates.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Dawson|first=Bill|title=Sandy + election results = re-energized talk of action against climate change|url=http://texasclimatenews.org/wp/?p=6145|accessdate=22 May 2014|newspaper=Texas Climate News|date=2012-11-24}}</ref> Gallego has voiced support for renewable and clean energy sources. The Sierra Club called Gallego a \"clean energy champion.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Impact of the 2012 Elections|url=http://content.sierraclub.org/politics-elections/impact-2012|accessdate=22 May 2014|newspaper=Sierra Club}}</ref> ''[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]]'' included Gallego in a list of the \"Top Five Climate Hawks\" who were elected to office in November 2012.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sheppard|first=Katie|title=5 Climate Hawks Who Won on Tuesday|url=http://www.motherjones.com/blue-marble/2012/11?page=4|accessdate=22 May 2014|newspaper=Mother Jones|date=11-8-2012}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBorn in Alpine, Gallego graduated from [[Sul Ross State University]] in 1982 with a bachelor\u2019s degree in [[political science]]. In 1985, he earned a [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] from the [[University of Texas School of Law]] in [[Austin, Texas|Austin]].<ref name=journal/>\n\nIn 2012, Gallego began drawing pension benefits from the state of Texas in addition to his annual congressional salary of $174,000.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pension Rules to Benefit 10 in Congressional Delegation|url=http://www.ketknbc.com/news/pension-rules-to-benefit-10-in-congressional-deleg|accessdate=22 May 2014|newspaper=Texas Tribune|date=7-9-2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=U.S. Rep. Pete Gallego (D)|url=http://www.texastribune.org/bidness/explore/pete-gallego/|work=Ethics Explorer|publisher=Texas Tribune|accessdate=22 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Pension Rules to Benefit 10 in Congressional Delegation|url=http://www.ketknbc.com/news/pension-rules-to-benefit-10-in-congressional-deleg|accessdate=19 August 2014|publisher=KETK-NBC|date=7-9-2013}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|Texas|Law}}\n*[[Hispanics in the United States]]\n*[[Mexican American|Mexican-Americans]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://gallego.house.gov/ Representative Pete Gallego] official U.S. House website\n*[http://petegallego.com/ Pete Gallego for Congress] \n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Texas/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Pete_Gallego_%5BD-23%5D}}\n*{{CongLinks | congbio = G000572 | ballot = Pete_Gallego | nndb = | votesmart = 5505 | govtrack = 412577 | opencong = 412577 | rollcall = 44851 | politifact = pete-gallego | fec = H2TX23124 | opensecrets = N00033541 | assets = | legistorm = | followthemoney = 1168 | ontheissues = TX/Pete_Gallego.htm | congress = pete-gallego/2164 | worldcat = np-gallego,%20pete%20p | c-span = petegallego | imdb = | bloomberg = | nyt = | wsj = | washpo= d1857250-4bbb-11e2-8758-b64a2997a921}}\n*[http://www.malc.org Mexican American Legislative Caucus]\n*[http://www.naleo.org/ National Association of Latino Elected Officials (NALEO)]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{USRepSuccessionBox |\n  state=Texas|\n  district=23 |\n  before=[[Quico Canseco]] | \n  after=[[Will Hurd]]<br>Elect |\n  start=January 3, 2013\n}}\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Tulsi Gabbard]]<br><small>D-[[Hawaii]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=''[[List of current members of the United States House of Representatives by seniority|United States Representatives by seniority]]''|years=381st}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Joe Garcia]]<br><small>D-[[Florida]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{TX-FedRep}}\n\n{{Persondata <!-- Metadata: see [[Wikipedia:Persondata]]. -->\n| NAME              =Gallego, Pete\n| ALTERNATIVE NAMES =\n| SHORT DESCRIPTION = American politician\n| DATE OF BIRTH     =1961-12-02\n| PLACE OF BIRTH    =[[Alpine, Texas]]\n| DATE OF DEATH     =\n| PLACE OF DEATH   